Section section_02 (Chars 9138–12774):
Section Summary: In his later years, Herbert Spencer was disheartened to see that his social and political doctrines were not widely accepted by a new generation of thinkers. Despite this, his contributions to the philosophy of life and mind remain significant. Spencer's philosophy emphasized the concept of evolution as a universal principle, governed by natural laws and processes, which he believed could explain all phenomena, including the growth of society and individual life. He proposed a unified theory that encompassed biology, psychology, sociology, and ethics, all of which were interconnected and governed by the principles of matter, motion, and force. Ultimately, Spencer's philosophy acknowledged the limitations of human understanding, recognizing that some mysteries, such as the ultimate reality, may be beyond human comprehension.
